|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|                                   0.051.150                                  |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

|==============================================================================|
|                              APPLICATION CHANGES                             |
|==============================================================================|

* Updated documentation to cover all new features and changes.
* Fixed a bug where users with the protected status were being identified as
  being privileged
* Overhauled the "Plugins" page of the "Settings" dialog, and added links to
  the documentation to the "Scripting", "Plugins", and "Advanced" pages.
* Added new feature toggles to the "Settings" menu
* Updated the "Settings" menu screenshot on the repo
* Disabling plugins in the settings menu now closes all Python editor
  windows
* Disabling plugins in the "Settings" dialog now closes all Python
  editor windows
* Disabling scripting in the "Settings" dialog now closes all script editor
  windows
* Fixed a bug where if the scripting engine was disabled while running,
  the "run script" button wouldn't be hidden on server windows
* The "style" and "plugins" directories entries are now hidden in the
  tools menu "directories" submenu if the style editor and plugins
  are disabled, respectively; change has also been made to the systray menu
* Added a new submenu to the tools menu: a list of plugins, allowing
  the user to open the plugin files in the Python editor
* When opening up a file in either the script editor or the Python editor,
  the application will no longer open multiple windows for the same file.
  If the file is already open in an editor, that editor is "shown" and the
  focus is switched to the open editor. This works for plugin files, scripts,
  and connection scripts.
* Added a new submenu in the settings menu: "tools", which allow users to
  toggle various features on and off (like scripting, plugins, etc.)
* Added a new icon for "tools" (for the new settings submenu) and "python"
  (for the new plugin file submenu)
* Added a new example plugin to the documentation
* Added a new command-line flag: -P, --disable-plugins. This flag disables
  plugins and prevents them from loading on startup
* Added a new command-line flag: --uninstall-all. This flag deletes all
  installed plugins, and is primarily meant for recovery if one or more 
  plugins are crashing MERK on load.
* Changed the window titles of the hotkey, ignore, and plugin managers to
  have "manager" in the title
* Changed the "Log Manager" entry in the "Tools" menu to "Logs"
* Log Manager now shows the output on the "Export" tab. This output
  display will update every time a log is selected, and every time
  an export setting is changed.
* Added a "Settings" section to the documentation, covering the settings
  dialog and menu.
* Entries in the Plugin Manager now provide more information than the name
  of the plugin and the version. Each entry shows the name, version, class
  name, file name, author, and size in memory of each plugin. Other than
  that, it works identically.
* Entries in the Hotkey Manager now look similar to the entries in the
  new Plugin Manager.
* Entries in the Ignore Manager now look similar to the entries in the
  other managers.
* The "no [WHATEVER ITEMS]" entry in all Hotkey, Plugin, and Ignore
  Managers are no longer selectable.
* Hotkeys are now saved to the configuration file automatically whenever
  they are added or removed. The "disk" button has been removed from
  the Hotkey Manager, and the "/bind save" command has been removed.
* Changed the documentation title (and the link to the documentation
  in the application) to reflect the document's actual filename.
* Removed the status bar from the Hotkey Manager; errors in adding or
  editing hotkeys are now reported to the user via messages boxes.
* Removed the status bar from the Ignore Manager, to match the other
  managers.
* Status messages in the Hotkey and Ignore managers are now relayed
  via message boxes, much like the Plugin Manager.
* Plugins can now have icons. If a PNG file is in the plugins directory
  with the same name as a plugin (example: plugin is named "example.py",
  and the PNG is named "example.png"), this PNG will be used as the
  plugin's icon, and will be displayed in the Plugin Manager. Icons are
  rendered at 32x32 pixels.
* Plugins can now be imported in ZIP files. Only PY and PNG files in the
  ZIP file are extracted into the plugins directory. Importing a zip
  file will not overwrite existing files with the same filename.
* Plugins in the form of a single Python file are now COPIED into the
  plugin directory rather than being MOVED.
* Fixed a bug in measuring the size of plugins in memory; attempting to
  measure the memory size of a plugin, in certain circumstances, could
  crash the client, but only while operating in PyInstaller. This
  feature has been removed, as its only use was to display to the user
  how much memory the plugin consumed.
* Added a new option to toggle whether to overwrite files when
  importing plugins. At the moment, only added to the configuration
  file. Set to "false" by default.
* The Plugin Manager can now export plugins to a ZIP archive. This will
  package a plugin file (and its icon, if it exists) into a ZIP output
  file selected by the user.
* Fixed a bug with eliding very long nicknames. If nicknames were greater
  than the nick pad length by a significant margin, they would occasionally
  be incorrectly elided, with the nickname being split up over two lines.
* Removed the "import" icon from the resource file, and now use the "open
  file" icon for the "import file" button in the Plugin Manager.
* Both the "export plugin" button and "remove plugin" buttons are now
  hidden in the Plugin Manager if there are no loaded plugins.
* Tweaks to the "Plugins" page of the "Settings" dialog
* Change to the wording of the "Plugins" entry in the "Tools" menu
* Clarified how hotkeys are used (and saved/loaded) in the documentation
* Changed to the wording of the "Hotkeys" entry in the "Tools" menu

|==============================================================================|
|                              PLUGIN API CHANGES                              |
|==============================================================================|

* Fixed a bug in the title() plugin Window class method; window titles
  were not being set (or returned) properly
* Fixed a bug where using the plugin Window class methods bind() and unbind()
  did not save hotkeys to the configuration file.
* Fixed a bug in the private() built-in Plugin method.
* New plugin Window class method: active(). This returns a boolean; True if
  the window is currently active, and False if not
* New plugin Window class method: position(). This returns a list; the first
  value in the list is the window's X value, the second value in the list
  is the window's Y value. If the position cannot be determined, both
  values will be set to 0.
* New plugin Window class method: size(). This returns a list; the first
  value in the list is the window's width, the second value in the list is
  the window's height. If the size cannot be determined, both values will
  be set to 0.
* New plugin Window class method: history(). This returns a list of strings
  representing the command history of a window's text input widget, in order
  of most recent to least recent. The maximum size of this list is, by
  default, 20 entries, unless changed in the settings dialog or with /config.
  If command history is turned off, this will return an empty list.
* New plugin Window class method: chat(). This returns a list of lists of
  strings representing the chat currently being displayed in the window. If
  the window is a server window, or there is no chat being displayed, this
  will return an empty list.
* New Plugin method: emojize(). This takes a string, converts and emoji
  shortcodes in it into emojis, and returns the altered string.
* Changes to the private() Plugin method: a new optional argument, a
  boolean, can be passed to the method. If the boolean is set to "true",
  then a private window will be created if none is found.
* New Plugin method: move(). This moves the main application window to a
  set location; if the new location would place the window someplace it can
  not be interacted with, the move fails. Returns "true" if the move is
  successful, and "false" if not.
* New Plugin method: resize(). This resizes the main application window.